<font color="#FF0000">MORE: AMNESTY AND PROTESTORS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Feb 14 18:51:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Pointman and Doc,<br><br>
&quot;That their motives were not as altruistic as claimed?&quot;<br><br>
Now there's a good thought.<br><br>
Many motivations have their roots in fear. Trying to put myself back in the mind of an 18 - 22 year old in the late 60's and early 70's, what in hell did any of us know about anything. Maybe we just got out of high school or college. I do realize that most of us spent our lives until then totally concentrated on ourselves, and maybe a circle of friends.<br><br>
I recall conversations with my friends in hushed and muted tones about Vietnam, and there were more strategies concocted to get out of it than I can remember. The 4F draft status was highly prized and generally envied. The guys with coke bottle glasses and asthma had it made, in our eyes! <br><br>
We looked at our leaders as wheezy, fat fingered old men who did nothing but spout cold war rhetoric. They weren't much of an inspiration! We saw the press reports of Vietnam. We saw the protestors.<br><br>
Protestors were a funny lot. They usually hung out in the &quot;coffee house&quot;, and similar places. They were as self centered as we were. They just expressed it differently. The one thing that stood out like a sore thumb was the protestor's contempt and intolerance of anything that would disrupt their lives. Boy, were they touchy! The &quot;establishment&quot;, they called it! Peace, and love, but don't try to enforce any rules!<br><br>
Another thing I recall from that age bracket is that we could be easily led around by the nose. &quot;Old men&quot; (older guys!) are usually too wise to be seduced into physical fight or protest. <br><br>
If you try to add it all up, as I have been trying to do, I guess it is fair to say that I wound up in the service because my &quot;establishment&quot; background taught me it was bad to be a criminal. I did not go to 'Nam because I liked killing. I knew nothing about it. I went because I &quot;had&quot; to. I &quot;feared&quot; the consequences and shame of not doing my duty. I could have just as easily wound up in the service in Korea or Germany, like some of my buddies did. <br><br>
I also think it is fair to say that the protestors cut and ran from the draft because of their inflated feelings of self importance, martyrs to a cause, fear, and all the rest of it.<br><br>
I think they were as frightened as I was, probably a whole lot more.  Somehow, hiding from the law as a felonious draft dodger was not my idea of a life, under any circumstances. This wasn't the French Underground of WW2!<br><br>
As I was not some mideval crusader on the search for the holy grail, the protestors were not Mother Theresa, either.<br>
Their &quot;cause&quot; was purely selfishness and fear, all the while being led around by the nose by their own propaganda machine. There is, however, no rationalization that will erase the fact that they deliberately broke the law.<br><br>
Why we let them back in this country is nothing more than pure slimey corrupt politics that invalidates every name and every ghost on The Wall.<br><br>
I guess I had to get that out.<br><br>
It still hurts. <br><br>
  
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


